Dimensionality Reduction - R Methods

C. Heiser, 2019

The purpose of this notebook is to perform dimensionality reduction techniques implemented in the R statistical computing language.

To benchmark these methods, we are using two single-cell RNA-seq datasets: * From Macosko, et al. (2015), mouse retina scRNA-seq data generated using DropSeq: GSM1626793 * From Herring, et al. (2018), mouse colon scRNA-seq data generated using inDrops: GSM2743164

The first set should be discrete, containing highly separable cell distributions from the mouse retina, where the latter will be continuous, representing hierarchical, branching cell states in the gut epithelium.

Both datasets have been preprocessed and feature-selected to allow for direct input to downstream dimensionality reduction algorithms (rather than first performing PCA to limit dimensional input). These methods are shown in dev/preprocess_and_filter.ipynb.

ZINB-WaVE

From Risso, et al. (2018), ZINB-WaVE is a zero-inflated negative binomial model for low-dimensional representations of scRNA-seq counts data. Available on Bioconductor.

Create SummarizedExperiment object from counts data, then perform ZINB-WaVE.

# transpose matrix to genes x cells format
colon_expt <- SummarizedExperiment(assays = list(counts=data.matrix(t(colon))))
# perform ZINB-WAVE analysis
colon_zinbwave <- zinbwave(colon_expt, K=2, epsilon=1000, verbose=T)

GLM-PCA

SIMLR

From Wang, et al. (2017), SIMLR is a multikernel learning approach to dimensionality reduction, clustering, and visualization of scRNA-seq counts data. Available on Bioconductor.

First on the colon data. SIMLR requires an expected number of clusters in the dataset. We can use SIMLR to estimate this.

# use SIMLR to estimate number of clusters in dataset for feeding into DR algorithm
# input is raw counts
colon_clu_est <- SIMLR_Estimate_Number_of_Clusters(t(colon), NUMC = 2:14)
print(which.min(colon_clu_est$K1))
[1] 5

Now we can normalize our counts data and feed it into the SIMLR algorithm with the expected number of clusters from above.

colon_norm <- arcsinh.norm(colon, margin=1) # normalize by arcsinh-tranforming fractional counts per gene
# perform SIMLR analysis with the estimated number of clusters from above
colon_SIMLR <- SIMLR(t(colon_norm), c = which.min(colon_clu_est$K1))
Computing the multiple Kernels.
# plot results
plot.DR(data.frame(colon_SIMLR$ydata), colorby = colon_SIMLR$y$cluster, name='SIMLR')
